The origin of the Aeuri people is a tale shrouded in mystery. Their Great Book
is said to contain the complete histories of all the races, their Gods and even
the Genesis of the world. Yet for that to be possible, the Aeuri must have
existed then to write down these histories. The Aeuri say, that when the Great
Book is finished, it will provide an answer to every question. Until then, it is
their purpose to keep filling it with new experiences.

A race of tiny, grey-haired humanoids, the Aeuri are as unnoticeable as a race
can be. Their physical appearance is nearly identical with one another, and
most times the only way to tell them apart are the clothes they wear.
An Aeuri does not age in conventional means, nor do they seem to exhibit any
physical growth. The birth of an Aeuri is an unremarkable affair: an Aeuri
is merely willed into being by the Great Book, completely in tune with its
child-like, bipedal body and with a singular focus to experience and to
record those experiences in the Great Book.

It is because of this task that they are considered to be the record-keepers
of the world. And it is this drive to learn and to record that consumes them
and drives them until they reach an ending, which other races might describe as
death. Upon the completion of its task, an Aeuri merely becomes a being of
pure knowledge, which is subsequently absorbed by the Great Book.

The Aeuri experience time differently compared to other races. Yet, they are
reluctant to take advantage of this in combat. As firm believers in the
inevitability of fate over the whimsical nature of Gods, the Aeuri folk take
pride in staying in the sidelines of history, letting matters unfold as they
are meant to. They believe that the purest form of history is not written by
those who win, but by those who can stay impartial across the aeons.

