 Ogres are poorly understood -- and generally best avoided -- by other
 sentient species. They are a barbaric brood with a penchant for
 cruelty, preying on the weak for sport as much as survival. They
 dwell in loosely organized might-makes-right societies, where the
 strong compete for dominance while the rest are subjugated or exiled.
 Ogres are taller than humans by heads and shoulders, but do not rival
 the giantkin in terms of sheer height. In terms of body mass, however,
 a full-grown ogre is a formidable sight, often up to several men wide.
 Ogres have hulking physiques, with broad chests, wide skulls and densely
 coiled muscles beneath flabby torsos and sagging paunches. Their wide
 mouths are lined with sharp teeth; their faces covered in warts
 and waxy scar tissue. Scars command respect among ogres, and
 disfigurement through battle is thought to be a form of ancestral
 blessing. Little is known about ogre reproduction. The bodies of ogres
 captured or slain in battle lack reproductive anatomy. Gendered
 ogres are rumored to exist, but are seldom if ever sighted in ogre
 encampments and raiding parties. If such aberrations exist at all,
 they are likely shunned from ogre society.

